Reaganomics, the economic policies implemented by President Ronald Reagan, faced criticism for several reasons. Critics argue that it led to increased income inequality, as the benefits of tax cuts were seen to disproportionately favor the wealthy. Additionally, while it aimed to reduce government spending, the policies resulted in significant budget deficits due to increased military spending and lower tax revenues. These factors contributed to the perception that Reaganomics did not achieve its intended goals of sustainable economic growth and fiscal balance.